==Net Zero Energy Concepts==
A net-zero building produces the same amount of energy it consumes <ref>http://www.sciencedirect.com.ezproxy.humboldt.edu/science/article/pii/S0378778810004639</ref>. A net zero building consumes no extra energy from the grid, meaning all energy consumed in the building is created through renewables on site <ref>
""Net Zero Energy Project." by Ty Newell and Ben Newell. ASHRAE Journal, 52.9 (2010): 88-89."</ref>. 

Reaching net-zero can be difficult and requires changes to the way the building consumes energy. An in-depth home energy audit should be performed to identify the appliances and the energy usage in the home. An in-depth home energy audit should also include finding ways to cut back on energy consumption and implementing useful tools in the house to help the residence keep track of energy consumption. 

Net Zero Energy buildings are becoming a more common option when people are searching for new homes. The whole concept of buying a house with no utilities bills can be both a cost effective and simple decision for most. Net zero energy construction and design is an efficiency oriented technique that focuses on conserving resources, conserving energy, and balancing those concepts while utilizing the highest performance appliances and systems available. 

According to Marzsal et al., "The Zero Energy Building (ZEB) concept is no longer perceived as a concept of a remote future, but as a realistic solution for the mitigation of CO2 emissions and/or the reduction of energy use in the building sector." <ref>
http://www.sciencedirect.com.ezproxy.humboldt.edu/science/article/pii/S0378778810004639</ref>

We will be analyzing CCAT's energy use and giving them suggestions on how they can reduce their energy use. The overall goal is to give suggestions for CCAT to become a net zero building by 2015. A Home Energy Audit of CCAT must be done, which will be a detailed report of what appliances are using the most energy. Our suggestions will also include an estimated cost for CCAT to run entirely off solar power.

Most case studies of Net Zero homes call for homes that are “Build tight, and ventilation right"<ref>
www.zeroenergyhouse.co.nz</ref>, this article suggest the combination and the implementation of renewable resources technology and energy conservation techniques, including an airtight seal help achieve net zero.

